{{for|the writer|Lawrence Clark Powell}} {{BLP sources|date=May 2009}} {{Infobox police officer |name = Laurence Powell |image = |caption = |birth_name = Laurence Michael Powell |birth_date = {{birth date and age|1962|8|26}}<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=hpEwDVuf0IgC&q=laurence+powell+lapd+1962&dq=laurence+powell+lapd+1962&hl=en&sa=X&ei=m7TeT6-rJqai2gXryuXgAQ&ved=0CDgQ6AEwAQ]</ref><ref>[http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=LA&p_theme=la&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EF6152DA8FD3B25&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM]</ref> |death_date = |badgenumber = |birth_place = [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], [[United States|U.S.]] |death_place = |nickname = |department = [[Los Angeles Police Department]] |service = Not Applicable |serviceyears = 1989 - 1992 |rank = Sworn in as an Officer - 1989 |awards = |relations = |laterwork = Convicted in connection to the [[Rodney King]] beating }}
'''Laurence Michael Powell''' (born August 26, 1962 in [[Los Angeles, California]]) is a former [[Los Angeles Police Department]] officer. He was one of the five officers involved in the beating of [[Rodney King]] on March 3, 1991.
==Background== Powell graduated from [[Crescenta Valley High School]]. He later enrolled in the police academy. <ref>http://www.time.com/time/specials/2007/la_riot/article/0,28804,1614117_1614084_1614517,00.html</ref>
==Rodney King incident and trial== On March 3, 1991, Powell and three other officers, Sgt. [[Stacey Koon]], Officer Theodore Briseno, and Officer Timothy Wind were videotaped repeatedly striking Rodney King with their police batons in [[Lake View Terrace]].<ref>{{cite web|title=RODNEY KING BEATING VIDEO Full length footage SCREENER|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sb1WywIpUtY|accessdate=28 June 2016|date=12 March 2015}}</ref> Officer Powell was partnered with Officer Wind at the time.
The Los Angeles District Attorney charged the four officers with assault with a deadly weapon and use of excessive force. A year later, after a change of venue from Los Angeles to [[Ventura County, California|Ventura]] County, a jury of ten whites, one Asian and one Hispanic, acquitted the four officers of the assault charge, but [[Hung jury|deadlocked]] on the excessive force charge for Powell. The verdict led to the [[1992 Los Angeles riots]].
The four officers were later indicted on federal charges for violating Rodney King's civil rights. Powell and Koon were convicted in 1993 and were sentenced to 30 months in prison.<ref>http://articles.latimes.com/1996-06-14/news/mn-14959_1_sentencing-guidelines</ref>
The 1992 song "Guerillas in the Mist" by [[Da Lench Mob]] uses a sample of the phrase "gorillas in the mist" uttered by Powell. The LAPD officer had used the phrase to describe a black family in a domestic dispute that he responded to just before stopping King, named after the 1988 film ''[[Gorillas in the Mist]]''.<ref>Quinn, Eithne. ''Nuthin' but a "G" Thang: The Culture and Commerce of Gangsta Rap''. New York: Columbia University Press, 2005. (See pp. 104-105.)</ref>
